 hip hop artists navigate the muddy waters of the "politics of authenticity" by creating art that is not bound by narrow conceptions of what it means to be Indigenous; instead, they flip the notion of "tradition" and create alternative visions of what being Indigenous means today, and what that might look like going forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHip-hopzNorth America. 0aIndian youthzNorth AmericaxMusic. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aRap (Music)xHistory and criticism. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Music. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846947840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438469478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438469478/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles